@nielsenb-jf You seems to conflate to different things.

A network unit is just a wrapper for podman network create which uses so called network drivers (bridge, macvlan, ipvlan), so called custom (or user defined) networks. There you choose the driver and the pass the name of the network to `podman run --network`.

`pasta` but also `slirp4netns`, `host`, `none`, `container:...` are so network modes that you can also give to `podman run --network`, they are special because they always exist and the network create command option have no meaning and cannot be mapped to them so that is why they are not "drivers".

@Luap99 You are absolutely right, I was conflating things. Simply omitting a network option in the container definition made my containers come up using pasta and they can see the "real" IP of requests. Thanks for the insight!

The [network unit documentation ](https://docs.podman.io/en/latest/markdown/podman-systemd.unit.5.html#driver-defaults-to-bridge) should probably point directly to the [network create driver documentation](https://docs.podman.io/en/latest/markdown/podman-network-create.1.html#driver-d-driver).

It still isn't fully clear to me why a container unit using a network created via a systemd unit uses the "bridge" network mode by default.
